        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: Deborah Knight</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        Hi, Brandon.  Catching up on all you are saying here. Very interesting discussions.<br><br>I have always had a belief that since God is no respector of persons, and because Jesus revealed Himself in all His glory to some people, then everyone would be given a chance to see and know Jesus in the same way before they would be punished for rejecting Him. <br><br>Satan does know God and still rejected Him so there may be some that would still reject Jesus out of pride or rebellion. For those, however, the book of Revealation says that death and hell are thrown into the lake of fire, this being called the second death. If we have eternal life as a gift from God through Jesus, then the opposite of that, to me, would be eternal death, or just ceasing to exist at the second death. <br><br>I was a little worried by some of the experiences you described in other posts, but upon reflection, they don't seem to be much different from some that other Christians say they have had. And the daily messages are very similar to those given in charismatic churches I have attended as people exercise the gifts of the Spirit in those meetings.<br><br>The only caution I would give you, as I think John has also, is to resist the pride that can come in when one is being used by God. It can happen to any of us, even happened to Elijah, when he thought he was the only one left that loved God and God told him He had 7000 more Elijah knew nothing about. We are the Body of Christ, and we each have our own special place and destiny. <br><br>The Apostle Peter lived and died, as we all will. The stories of all his successes as well as the mistakes of his life, blessed those of his generation and still blesses us as we read of him.  We each have our own testaments to what we know of the love and goodness and mercy of God to share, wherever we are in God's time and plan, but we are just one of many millions.  I think Peter may have faced a temptation that I sometimes fall in to, to revel and enjoy what I know of God's love, all by myself. Jesus had to tell Peter three times to 'feed his sheep'...that what we know and feel for God is to be shared to encourage and feed the faith of others. So keep sharing, Brandon, even your mistakes and corrections, and God will give the increase. </span>
