        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: John J. Farren</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        Regarding what I’ve referred to as “infallibly efficacious (actual) grace,” I must immediately disassociate myself from Reginald Garrigou-Lagrange and some of the so-called “Neo-thomists,” whose doctrines on actual grace, while claiming to be those of Aquinas, are most certainly not. For excellent reading in this area read the two best, Jacques Maritain, [B]God and the Permission of Evil[/B],  and Charles Journet, [COLOR="blue"]The Meaning of Grace.[/COLOR]<br><br>You wrote regarding actual grace, “[COLOR="blue"]I can see perhaps him putting all his power into having them choose it, but in the end if they are 100% dead set against believing it, there's not much God can do.[/COLOR]” This is similar to what Augustine held. I do not accept this as a sufficient solution. It is one of three major ways that attempt to deal with actual grace.<br><br>You also wrote, “[COLOR="blue"]I find a complication in God being able to have someone choose what he wants them to choose, for I don't know if that is truly free.[/COLOR]” God, the First Cause of all being, never interferes with the creature’s free will/choice .. but rather PERFECTS it. God’s grace does not diminish free will but rather brings it to complete perfection in the order of being, freedom, fullness, and goodness. (An aside > The Beatific Vision perfects us not merely in infallibly preventing us from doing evil but rather removes from us totally the imperfection that permits us to fail.)<br><br>I myself have found much enlightenment in the great truths of faith of our Catholic Church in the writings of Hinduism, especially the [B]Bhagavad-Gita[/B] .. and the teachings of Mahayana Buddhism and Zen Buddhism. Always it is necessary to separate the chaff from the wheat. And with the grace of the Holy Spirit one must discern and judge and reject and accept all that one encounters. For centuries people almost worship the popes and the curia -- I say almost -- as they were meant to worship Christ. The popes of Vatican II and Post-Vatican II have helped us toward a greater legitimate (true) freedom in the lives of faith we must lead and in our attitudes toward this very church that Jesus founded.<br><br>You asked whether it is permitted for a Catholic to hold the belief in universal salvation. In what I have explained I see nothing that is opposed to anything we must believe as Catholics. Some might disagree with me .. but surely some would agree with me.<br><br>Brandon, you really share some good thinking. I seldom get caught by postings .. but often you do catch me.<br>Blessing in Jesus and Mary, John            (JohnJFarren)</span>
