        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: John J. Farren</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        JMJ / MMM     27 July 2010<br>Hello Brother Brandon --<br>It's good to be back in the thinking circle again.<br><br>It is true “<span style="color:blue;">that parts of the Church are very legalistic.</span>” I’ve often heard Catholics, who have a reasonable grasp of the faith, make statements (sometimes dogma, sometimes morals) that are simply false. In past ages our Catholic Church has been extremely legalistic. So we must consider ourselves in the Post Vatican II time very blessed because this grossly excessive legalism has been tremendously diminished, thanks to a great in pouring of the Holy Spirit, and several very saintly popes. I do thank God, Brandon, that I never became a priest. I would have obligations that now and then would put me between a rock and a hard place.<br><br>	At the same time we must realize that the Church must have laws and that proper laws are to be obeyed. And here again we have a difficulty. Who shall decide about these laws? We are not to be BLIND sons of God. We are to be intelligent, and respectful and obedient sons of God. There have never been easy solutions to these intricate problems. Let each of us pray to the Holy Spirit for guidance as we strive to be good sons of God and good sons of the Church.<br><br>I <em>can</em> understand a human being or an angel truly deserving an eternal hell. Many of our sins are sins or weakness or confusion. But there ARE people who have chosen to commit (“baptize”) themselves to Satan absolutely .. and at the same time to freely and with full knowledge to hate Jesus Christ and the Holy Spirit and the Father. They KNOW what they are doing .. and they truly WANT to do it. There are small groups of these people in every major city of the world.<br><br>IF we were able to converse with someone in hell (assuming there IS a human being in hell) and offer them grace and escape and Heaven, they would curse us and damn us. Such a person would truly WANT to be in hell rather than in Heaven.<br><br>It is proper to say that, in a sense, God never damns anyone to hell. But it is also accurate to say that there are people, deeply “matured” in deliberate evil, who freely choose [I]to damn themselves[/I]. “[COLOR="blue"]Better to rule in hell than to serve in Heaven[/COLOR]” .. from Dante’s [B]IL INFERNO[/B]. We have been made “in the image and likeness of God,” and in the psalms we are said to be “[COLOR="blue"]little less than gods.[/COLOR]” The power of intellect we have and the terrible mighty power of our free choice makes us destined to “[COLOR="blue"]become like God[/COLOR]” [B]1 John[/B] 3:1-2 .. or the complete inverse in the order of being.</span>
