        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: <a href="brandon.html">Rev. Brandon A. Olivares</a></strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        John I will tell you truly and honestly the problem I have been having. Firstly, I am not able to bring myself to believe in an eternal hell. Even if the pope himself came and told me I was wrong, I still couldn't imagine that God could send someone to hell forever, or even for very long. I think that God loves everyone so much as people allow him to, and no one is proud of the mistakes they know they made. I like the life review idea that the article mentioned. People may accuse themselves and may have to forgive themselves, but never do I think God would accuse them.<br><br>My second problem is that I begin to feel that parts of the Church are very legalistic. I've been around people who think that a white lie will send you to hell, or a child doing something his parents said not to do. I believe that Jesus told us to follow the spirit of the law, and that love for God and neighbor was more important than the letter of the law and the rituals.<br><br>My problem is that there are some things the Church says certain things are wrong, that I am having a hard time seeing as wrong. For example, there is a practice that comes from the east, called reiki, which is a form of healing. The US bishops condemned it last year, saying it was spiritually dangerous for Christians. On the other hand, Pope John Paul II gave several priests and nuns permission to practice it back in the '90s. To me it seems that if people are practicing it, and they are healing people physically, mentally, emotionally, and they are only helping people in every way possible, that there is no problem with it. Jesus said that we would know them by their fruits, and the fruits of the work of many people involved in practices such as this are very good.<br><br>I think that many people are reluctant to explore outside of the Church. I believe, however, that though the Church may have the truth, it doesn't mean that there is not also truth in other beliefs and philosophies, in some way, even truth not necessarily covered within the Church. Not everything good is exclusively contained within the Christian tradition. Even Augustine struggled to figure out which teachings of Plato were compatible with Christianity, and which were not, but he did not simply throw all of Plato's teachings away for being Pagan. I believe that we can learn much from other systems. I think that we should be cautious, but not fear needlessly that which is foreign for only the fact that it is foreign.<br><br>It's just something that's really been bothering me. Since you seem very reasonable, I just wanted to post my struggle here.<br><br>I hope all is well with you.</span>
